<h1>@HI{{mae ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{mae ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} <strong>@HI{{mae ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
<li> <em>quantifier(period)</em> <strong>@HI{{mae ni}}</strong>, @V2{{}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
This sentence pattern indicates that @V2{{}} happens before whatever is stated in the subordinate clause.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book}}he @KJ{{come}}ru <strong>mae ni</strong>, @KJ{{day^book^word}}wo
      @KJ{{exertion^strong}}shimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I studied Japanese before I came to Japan.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{eat^matter}}no <strong>mae ni</strong>, @KJ{{hand}}wo@KJ{{wash}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wash my hands before eating.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}sanha 1@KJ{{time^interval}}<strong>mae ni</strong>, @KJ{{exit}}kakemashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Tanaka left an hour ago.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The verb before <strong>@HI{{mae ni}}</strong> is always non-past even if the sentence itself is in the past.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mae ni}}</strong> is used when the speaker something is going to take place. If the speaker
is unsure when the event might take place, @HI{{uchi ni}} should be used instead.
</p>

